    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-11-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-11-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="117"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_IO1">IO</gloss> Files: US/A/152</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by Randolph Harrison of the United
                        States Delegation Staff of Advisers</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New York</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-11-20">November 20,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>Mr. Fack of the Netherlands Delegation</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. van Roijen, of the Netherlands Delegation</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Mr. Randolph Harrison</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Both Mr. van Roijen and Mr. Fack, of the Netherlands Delegation, sought me out to
                    express their deep concern and disappointment over the action of the United
                    States in withdrawing its support from the Netherlands for a seat on the <gloss
                        target="#t_ECOSOC1">ECOSOC</gloss>. Mr. Fack said that losing the vote of
                    the United States was bad enough in itself, but since the act of the United
                    States was generally known due to newspaper publicity, he felt that it would
                    undoubtedly influence other nations to withdraw their support from the
                    Netherlands. Mr. van Roijen and Mr. Fack both expressed the earnest hope that
                    the decision of the United States on this subject was not final and that it
                    would reinstate the Netherlands in its slate.</p>
            </div>
